[{"id":27660,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>COOH</mi></math>&nbsp;group present in</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21ddb3e9-c950-4dc5-8e6c-088424aea058-01bd4eb6-60d5-499f-983a-bf9d87e7851f-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 458px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27629,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A, C and D Only","A, B and E Only","A and C Only","A and B Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{A}, \\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{D}$ produce $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with aqueous $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$ solution.\nA, C, D acids are stronger acid than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$ (Carbonic acid)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27679,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["III $ < $ II $ < $ IV $ < $ I","I $ < $ III $ < $ II $ < $ IV","IV $ < $ II $ < $ III $ < $ I","II $ < $ IV $ < $ III $ < $ I"],"answer":0,"solution":"The increasing order of the acidity of the carboxylic acids is III $ < $ II $ < $ IV $ < $ I. In aromatic acids, electron withdrawing groups like $\\mathrm{Cl},-\\mathrm{CN},-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ increases the acidity, whereas electron releasing groups like $\\mathrm{CH}_3,-\\mathrm{OH},-\\mathrm{OCH}_3,-\\mathrm{NH}_2$ decreases the acidity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":27687,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["b $ < $ d $ < $ a $ < $ c","d $ < $ a $ < $ c $ < $ b","d $ < $ a $ < $ b $ < $ c","a $ < $ d $ < $ c $ < $ b"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":27651,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> dry ether <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>Heat</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>OI</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>Mg</mi></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow></mover><munder><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Butanoic</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>acid</mi></mrow></munder></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$B>D>E>A>C$","$D>B>E>A>C$","$C>A>B>D>E$","$D>E>B>A>C$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Carboxylic acids are stronger acids than phenols because the carboxylate anion is stabilized by equivalent resonance structures. Thus, D and E are more acidic than A, B, and C.<br><br>For the carboxylic acids, the $-NO_2$ group in D is an electron-withdrawing group ($-I, -R$), which stabilizes the conjugate base, making D more acidic than E.<br><br>For the phenols, electron-withdrawing groups increase acidity while electron-donating groups decrease it. The $-NO_2$ group in B is electron-withdrawing, making it more acidic than A. The $-OCH_3$ group in C is electron-donating ($+R > -I$), making it less acidic than A. Thus, the order for phenols is B $>$ A $>$ C.<br><br>Combining these, the overall descending order of acidity is D $>$ E $>$ B $>$ A $>$ C.<br><br>Answer: $D>E>B>A>C$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27682,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Etard reaction","Wolff-Kischner reaction","Rosenmund reaction","Hell-volhard-zelinsky reaction"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>This reaction is known as HVZ reaction.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4f9b8036-e7ee-4751-b47e-433fb887c796-image.png\" style=\"width: 522px; height: 102px;\" /></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, &quot;sans serif&quot;;\">Treatment with bromine and a catalytic amount of phosphorus leads to the selective <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo></math>bromination of carboxylic acids.</span></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27639,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/39c1e85b-cc77-47b8-9509-33046aee8348-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 143px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6ae73b4d-ac46-49db-a8ed-a07ad83d8189-image.png\" style=\"width: 248px; height: 150px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a7a995b2-3858-4c56-98a0-7cf433aedf36-image.png\" style=\"width: 248px; height: 131px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/faa48d79-06f6-40e5-bdec-262b38be2c9b-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 102px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In the first step bromine attacks the carbon-carbon double bond by electrophilic addition reaction mechanism and forms the bromonium&nbsp;cyclic intermediate. In the presence of sodium bicarbonate carboxylic acid group present in the reactant&nbsp;converts to carboxylate ion. This carboxylate ion opens the cyclic bromonium ion ring and forms the desired product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bdaeac43-97bd-4440-b424-f4895151620b-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 228px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27680,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["(i) $\\mathrm{NaBH}_4$, (ii) Raney $\\mathrm{Ni} / \\mathrm{H}_2$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4$, (ii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6$, (ii) $\\mathrm{DIBAL-H}$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6$, (ii) $\\mathrm{SnCl}_2 / \\mathrm{HCl}$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DqPDNn_rT2INu968wTx25q8PxzHtySEZCcbtVk5tVr8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":27663,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eeed523f-8ce7-4824-922a-eacc9a8c74c2-image.png\" style=\"width: 112px; height: 186px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a166754-69a5-4828-885a-a4c08db852ef-image.png\" style=\"width: 147px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d478922-fda9-4181-a1cd-ffff32e4ece3-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0fbe9d4c-9cfd-4267-a16f-cf1e5e45d785-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 145px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Isomer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;on heating with sodalime gives toluene,hence it is an acid.Moreover since it has&nbsp;Degree of unsaturation 5 therefore it is an aromatic carboxylic acid.Since Carboxylic acid on heating gives toluene&nbsp;,therefore it is having&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group attached to the benzene ring.</p><p>Now it forms single isomer on halogenation, therefore&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group must be attached at para position with respect to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi></math>&nbsp;group.</p><p>Hence correct option is 1.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/394bbbfd-ceb6-44ca-a213-2335be70abcb-image.png\" style=\"width: 316px; height: 300px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27637,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/825774a3-db3d-45a2-bdb3-1becacb9bd9b.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 94px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/59870980-f498-4bd3-8da1-9138418bff01.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 86px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/90d39f45-43b2-4fe8-aee3-78d4e6e75e56.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 97px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1a666b5-51ee-4ea3-973d-908ae709c475.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 79px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a halogenating agent. The carboxylic acid group of reactant changes to acid chloride. The acid chloride formed reacts with primary amine to give secondary amide. The secondary amide undergo reduction with lithium aluminium hydride to give secondary amine.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5546dec6-cec8-48ad-a320-e802a2d65c26.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 196px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27691,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Phenol","Benzoic acid","Butanal","Benzaldehyde"],"answer":3,"solution":"Benzaldehyde does not contain $\\alpha$ - hydrogen. Hence goes for cannizarro's reaction forming alcohol and acid","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27656,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp; group attached with carbonyl bond will decrease reactivity of acid derivative towards hydrolysis. For halogen&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;dominate over&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;therefore, acid chloride is most reactive. As extent of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect&nbsp;increases, reactivity decreases. Overall, order of reactivity is:<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56ba87b0-a548-4ac8-8b12-0d37a5d31f1d-image.png\" style=\"width: 483px; height: 141px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27676,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>IV</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"The rate of hydrolysis will depend on how likely a molecule is to accepting &nbsp;<math><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp; ions. Rate of hydrolysis&nbsp;<math><mi>α</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi></math>&nbsp; effect or <math><mo>-</mo><mi>I</mi></math> of ester.&nbsp;<math><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>I</mi></math>. <math><mo>-</mo><mi>N</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp; is a strong <math><mi>E</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>G</mi></math> (Electron withdrawing group),<math><mo>-</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></math> is a weak <math><mi>E</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>G</mi></math> and <math><mi>O</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> is an <math><mi>E</mi><mi>D</mi><mi>G</mi></math>(Electron donating group).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Acidic character <math><mi>&#945;</mi></math> stability of conjugate base (anion)<br /><br />Stability of anion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math><br /><br />Hence greater the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect greater will be the acidity<br /><br />Order of -I-effect <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> Hence, order of acidity &nbsp;will be<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>NC</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27693,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["propanoic acid and ammonium salt","ethanoic acid and ammonium salt","methylamine salt and ethanoic acid","ethylamine salt and methanoic acid"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{~N} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\stackrel{\\mathrm{H}^{+}}{\\longrightarrow} \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{NH}_2+\\mathrm{HCOOH}$. Therefore it gives only one mono chloroalkane.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27671,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math> convert ester into alcohol by reduction, it does not reduce <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math> bond between carbon atoms.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/357f8ad0-6dc7-4e2a-b979-7f3cabea8072-image.png\" style=\"width: 804px; height: 90px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27633,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Major product B is $\\rightarrow$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uDQz7Od7wcNvPL5SEFlPOYKdUmi9Ys-ewMJDxeJAxIs.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Total number of $\\pi$ bonds in $B$ are 5","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27665,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mrow></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> is very selective and usually used to reduce acid into alcohol.</p><p>Borane is commonly used for the reduction of carboxylic acids in the presence of esters, lactones, amides, halides and other functional groups. In addition, borane rapidly reduces aldehydes, ketones, and alkenes.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27683,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["​<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed57dd2d-d997-4c61-aa49-a75d99cf77f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 128px; height: 220px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc62bb74-aa4b-4f6d-99cf-6475eca20a62-image.png\" style=\"width: 178px; height: 127px;\" />​","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fa79ef7b-21fa-4db1-a39f-de21689f762d-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 159px;\" />​","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66d7dcde-1929-498f-8254-8038ba2dd764-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 142px;\" />​"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img height=\"138\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11cd197a-69fa-47ca-8a3a-5a42213a905a-image.png\" width=\"210\" /></p>Compound (A)&nbsp;gives a white precipitate when warmed with alcoholic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>means it contain a removable chloride&nbsp;atom(Benzylic position)<sub>.</sub>&nbsp;Oxidation of (A) gives an acid (B), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>. (B) easily forms anhydride on heating. Means both acid should be ortho position of each other.<p><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f739a781-ac88-4863-8eac-590d7792d214-image.png\" style=\"width: 613px; height: 305px;\" /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27638,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ffa5264b-5a31-4a42-b546-9f836565ffc4.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d3ec2f57-a8ea-4093-9e7d-52605c4da0a1.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 105px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a140b78-b492-42aa-bcce-479fb0de115a.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 111px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33a5e242-9a46-45c5-924e-22906a181911.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 131px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Lithium aluminium hydride, is a reducing agent that is commonly used in modern organic synthesis. It is a nucleophilic reducing agent that is best suited for reducing multiple polar bonds such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>. It can reduce carbonyl compounds to alcohols and amides to amines.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;is not effected during this reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb16d825-61ff-4c79-9899-05c99238b64e.png\" style=\"width: 666px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27630,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Z-CwxnLUSraQ1mGPePgJXSxJ5xoA-J4eQoT4QQESsNE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27652,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(a) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math> (Hydrolysis of ester)</p><p>(b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math> (Reduction of ester)</p><p>(c) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>SnCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math> (Reduction followed by hydrolysis)</p><p>(d)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ecc96e1-eabc-41d6-8516-182cdaefd424-image.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 90px;\" />&nbsp;(Nucleophillic addition reaction)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27632,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5XkGtDw71thZ_VUAkwdyqbdjReYa9BdUb3JKmXIoSnk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3Hye5f99350eA5573bzozF5rEewIQvRGaIM7dsg_Bf8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wnwMxo_7XA3FT6VJWpCvB64iiEiZJtYeXinASHBeiUw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dXn4czn2gRtAIHpYmFvP3SuNxgRQ6hvGALWXIHDMVK4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"HVZ Reaction\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gwyFIaRIgGJbTqI-FY4E_J2RkXLnPGkxuAue8CNGQ8w.original.fullsize.png\"><br />SECTION - B","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27670,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/025580cc-a238-437f-92b5-943bc721531d-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 129px;\" /></p><br />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4119bec6-944a-4c78-bdad-fc6b091046e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/159706ba-fa12-4622-9789-c72c8bb39290-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/187c93d4-fcc8-40bd-93af-aeff698192fa-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 130px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c014ab9-cf3a-401a-99f0-dc350a68c76e-image12.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 106px;\" /><br />Alkaline <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></math> oxidise&nbsp;benzylic carbon to the carboxylic acid.</p><p>Alkenes react with acidified potassium permanganate. Potassium Permanganate is a strong oxidant, and will initially convert the double bond to two alcohol (OH) groups.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27657,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","Alkaline <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;in presence of acidic medium shows oxidation reaction.&nbsp;</p><p>It converts carbon into acid if carbon is connected to benzene group directly and having at least one hydrogen with it then it can be converted into acid otherwise not. As shown below:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b447cb72-1ac4-4260-ae3f-c65b174dfe44-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 253px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27684,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c7283c3-2dd8-42ca-b561-61a2f3b4dfb0-image.png\" style=\"width: 182px; height: 78px;\" />","<math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>COOH</mtext> </mrow> </math>","<math><mrow>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>3</mn>  </msub>  <mtext>COOH</mtext></mrow></math>","<math><mrow>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>3</mn>  </msub>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mtext>COOH</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ammonia reacts with carboxylic acid to form ammonium carboxylate (B). Which on heating form amide (C). Amide on reaction with bromine and KOH&nbsp;undergo Hoffmann Bromamide reaction to form amine with one carbon less.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Hoffmann</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>bromamide</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>degradation</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>KOH</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27650,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3c6661f2-a5d2-4615-a73e-da4c4be666f1-67f8c20e-d492-410c-bed9-f0fb2bea1948-image.png\" style=\"width: 429px; height: 72px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/30e0e91e-6261-4879-b0cc-1b21fb009ed8-image.png\" style=\"width: 492px; height: 45px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/82f54392-b390-455c-860a-ab7388c5ced3-779c9799-85f0-4040-8160-0b1cfa14df47-image.png\" style=\"width: 402px; height: 46px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7244ae75-8c6b-49ee-8a0c-549e2592b9d7-image.png\" style=\"width: 410px; height: 50px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71fedead-2724-448d-b2e6-d2cad180ab1e-image.png\" style=\"width: 624px; height: 124px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27685,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{HCHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Esterification reaction is involved\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8-urAjhehmsKRijWUmrGimh4x731aCiK4R5VOBBrmzU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":27654,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>/</mo></math> ether, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Mg</mi><mo>/</mo></math> ether, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ac36412-d6ae-4eb3-8076-233700d34232-image.png\" style=\"width: 1106px; height: 170px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27673,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00kGSxKaFOpGgf9v_g65Oy9JdIoKOoPA4fzH96eFoAY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lUJF9OOv18EqWn5Mcac2FcZCpOGK5yepZHVkZfTrTzA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rTlVfWG62LyH8IxBnHBhH5XOij3bi5ZLKnwad6b7vIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XVAigqCcOXIABJyTp_E_qIwUm0URkSB5m-wnKLKm7Rk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eTSGo49aRK-_kmIdm94okiFJcdaZCnoQLOO3k9hoIQo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27672,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the mentioned structures&nbsp;<math><msup><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> will get added to the carbon having slight positive charge.<br /><br />Presence of <math><mtext>C</mtext><mtext>l</mtext></math> increases the positive charge whereas an electron donating group like <math><mtext>N</mtext><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> decreases the tendency.<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>M</mtext></math> or <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>I</mtext></math> group<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math> and <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br />Hence, the correct order will be:<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b5c0226c-a62e-42a7-8d33-561f2092b726-image.png\" style=\"width: 565px; height: 141px;\" /></p><p><img height=\"142\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8c61ef6-c2c1-4121-8e4b-9a055c04bd3f-image.png\" width=\"450\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c_n0EjvFgKMuxdALDlJFAU2HhP58wehMW_XMTXwaDME.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/P7wbZ-bHgm1Ui0BqxGlSgAq4vDkTS6UpQi0ZVOcSyGI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/v4apkzB6hZn1arP9pp-AkvyLpTACuDz5Zi-5ER28AaU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dub3OcY7XY4044kcOJMKLFUeGnxCdNzHByLN7Zn4Jog.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Concept - Those compounds which are more acidic than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$ can gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with aq. $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.<br />Release $\\mathrm{CO}_2 \\uparrow$ gas with aq. NaHCO 3<br />$\\Rightarrow[\\text { A.S. }]_{\\text {Comp. }} \\gt [\\text { A.S. }]_{\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3}$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option 1,2 and 3 gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option (4) Not gives $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27658,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6e73fc71-8059-43ed-b158-b802674247ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 226px; height: 76px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0873efbc-b2ac-42df-b55c-1ced6b48ee97-a5086a9d-592b-47c0-91c8-ca3906359ac6-image.png\" style=\"width: 233px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a3e8e127-c30c-4e10-b1d9-fc4ded6f5269-image.png\" style=\"width: 181px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eabae4ed-b893-45cf-85b4-f5bea2f7869e-image.png\" style=\"width: 236px; height: 83px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>&nbsp;is diisobutylaluminium&nbsp;hydride.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> can not reduce double bond. It can reduce cyclic ester.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d19ddf57-a11d-4a94-be8f-164bc266f656-image.png\" style=\"width: 445px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27620,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["2-Chloropropanoic acid","3-Chloropropanoic acid","1-Chloropropane","2-Chloropropane"],"answer":0,"solution":"Step 1: Hydrolysis of the nitrile.<br>Propanenitrile on basic hydrolysis followed by acidic workup gives propanoic acid:<br>$CH_3-CH_2-C \\equiv N \\xrightarrow[(ii)\\ H_3O^+]{(i)\\ OH^-/H_2O/\\Delta} CH_3-CH_2-COOH$<br><br>Step 2: Hell$-$Volhard$-$Zelinsky (HVZ) reaction.<br>Propanoic acid has an $sp^3$ $\\alpha$-carbon bearing two $\\alpha$-hydrogens. In the HVZ reaction, $Cl_2$ in the presence of red phosphorus selectively replaces one $\\alpha$-hydrogen by chlorine, giving the $\\alpha$-chloro acid after aqueous workup:<br>$CH_3-CH_2-COOH \\xrightarrow[(iv)\\ H_2O]{(iii)\\ Cl_2/\\text{Red P}} CH_3-CH(Cl)-COOH$<br><br>Hence, the major product $P$ is $2$-chloropropanoic acid, which corresponds to option $(1)$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null}]